@article{Vega2006,
abstract = {The vapor-liq. equil. of three recently proposed water models have been computed using Gibbs-Duhem simulations. These models are TIP4P/Ew, TIP4P/2005, and TIP4P/ice and can be considered as modified versions of the TIP4P model. By design TIP4P reproduces the vaporization enthalpy of water at room temp., whereas TIP4P/Ew and TIP4P/2005 match the temp. of max. d. and TIP4P/ice the melting temp. of water. Recently, the m.p. for each of these models has been computed, making it possible for the first time to compute the complete vapor-liq. equil. curve from the triple point to the crit. point. From the coexistence results at high temp., it is possible to est. the crit. properties of these models. None of them is capable of reproducing accurately the crit. pressure or the vapor pressures and densities. Addnl., in the cases of TIP4P and TIP4P/ice the crit. temps. are too low and too high, resp., compared to the exptl. value. However, models accounting for the d. max. of water, such as TIP4P/Ew and TIP4P/2005 provide a better est. of the crit. temp. In particular, TIP4P/2005 provides a crit. temp. just 7 K below the exptl. result as well as an extraordinarily good description of the liq. densities from the triple point to the crit. point. All TIP4P-like models present a ratio of the triple point temp. to the crit. point temp. of about 0.39, compared with the exptl. value of 0.42. As is the case for any effective potential neglecting many body forces, TIP4P/2005 fails in describing simultaneously the vapor and the liq. phases of water. However, it can be considered as one of the best effective potentials of water for describing condensed phases, both liq. and solid. In fact, it provides a completely coherent view of the phase diagram of water including fluid-solid, solid-solid, and vapor-liq. equil. [on SciFinder (R)]},
