acter of amphiphilic solutes, with their hydrophobic and hydrophilic faces, presents a special challenge for theory and experiment. Here a consensus on the 2D-IR interpretation has not yet been achieved; this lack of accord impedes the understanding of, for example, biochemical solutes and interfaces. We argue that the influence of hydrophobic groups on water jumps is only modest and well accounted for by an excluded volume effect in the HB exchange process. Conversely, hydrophilic groups have an important influence when their HB strength with water differs significantly from that of the water-water HB. The power of 2D-IR is argued to be accompanied by subtleties that can lead to just the opposite and, in our view, erroneous conclusion. We close with a prediction that a hydrophobic surface offers an arena in which the dynamics of "dangling" water OHs, bereft of a HB, could provide a 2D-IR confirmation of water jumps.},
